A new science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to ponder the need for a new science that could be just as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a century ago.
The majority of researchers assume that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
In view of the major challenges, it is believed that there is only little left to be discovered.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unresolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose exploration requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Secondly, data collection, which includes works related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solution is to be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
In many places, it is believed that the most difficult part of the work would be to utilize already known laws of nature with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could dispute that?
The models of today do function, indeed.
A growing group of scientists points out phenomena that cannot be explained as well with the current theories.
These problems do occur more frequently, but are also cleverly avoided because the science that would explain these problems simply does not exist.
This lacking science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In the individual scientific disciplines, the knowledge is fairly well established.
In view of the major challenges, it is believed that there is only little left to be discovered.
The chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – there are indeed a few things in our body that we still don't understand, but it can be assumed that the fundamental mechanisms of the interaction between cells and molecules are known.
In addition, there are the new social sciences that focus on humans and societies.
In each of these areas – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well established and largely uncontroversial.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest of cases, a scientist is an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are so different.
We cannot find answers to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
Let's consider the context of the preceding texts and summaries. The current German source sentence is "Man denke beispielsweise an das Gehirn." This sentence is a good example of how the current translation style remains consistent. It also seems to be related to the idea of complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction occurs on the basis of the principles of physics. The information thus conveyed is transmitted due to the laws of electricity.
There is also a system of specialized cells that communicate by exchanging chemical substances and thereby transmit information.
During the interaction between two brains, a new level is added: Here, information exchange occurs through language, signs, and concepts.
On every level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are suitable theories that explain the processes on each individual level.
Information is exchanged between the individual levels as well, but there is no science that could even attempt to explain this exchange of information.
To compensate for this lack, some researchers have attempted to redefine the instrumentation for explaining processes within a level in order to apply it to another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" on the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanation patterns works quite well, but the underlying problem is not resolved in this way: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the individual levels, and how is it transmitted?
Now, nearly all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this shameful lack of knowledge about how the overall system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary researchers who gathered in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science".
The researchers come from various countries and fields of study and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
Alongside scientists from relevant disciplines, experts in art theory, psychiatrists, linguists, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discussion.
The predominant part of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," where one adjusts and supplements the scientific foundations of a level on another.
Others, however, hold that a completely new approach is required.
Many scientists believe that scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge from scientists who currently lack access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Free thinking is often underestimated.
Most activities that take place under the banner of "science" have, similarly to their counterparts in the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
One believes that developing countries need to build similar resources as industrialized countries. This could, however, suffocate creative thinking.
Many young researchers are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas originate from laboratories and research centers that are not affiliated with the large institutions.
The most sophisticated approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came from the Soviet Union for twenty years, where there was a shortage of computing capacity at every turn.
The most groundbreaking and, in the truest sense of the word, world-changing insights in the field of physics over the past few decades did not come from the expected innovation hubs, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that has contributed to important insights for cognitive scientists.
And the most radical new ideas in the area of second-generation artificial intelligence (so-called "autonomous agents") come today from Prague.
The most groundbreaking scientific achievements have gone down in history.
As Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, this changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July marked the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified where explanations need to be found.
One will also incorporate further researchers from innovative regions into this group in order to then identify those problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discovered, as one may put it.
Um diese Herausforderungen zu meistern, ist es notwendig, dass sich Wissenschaftler auf dezentraler Basis zusammenarbeiten, wie es die Gruppe "Foundations of Information Science" aus Paris tut.
